    {
      "step_id": "a6ac0395",
      "step_index": 2,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "**Key motifs identified**\n- **Two amide carbonyls (urea/amide-like):**\n  - `O=C(Nc1ccccc1)N1...` = an **anilide/urea-type** carbonyl attached to an aniline ring.\n  - `N(C(=O)c3ccncc3)` = **tertiary amide** attached to a **pyridine** ring.\n- **Aromatic rings:**\n  - **Phenyl** (`c1ccccc1`) = lipophilic aromatic surface.\n  - **Pyridine** (`c3ccncc3`) = aromatic heterocycle; H-bond acceptor N (weakly basic).\n- **Bicyclic/bridged tertiary amide nitrogen in a rigid ring system:**\n  - The nitrogen bearing `C(=O)pyridyl` is **tertiary amide N** (non-protonatable).\n- **No obvious protonatable aliphatic amine:**\n  - Ring nitrogens are **amide/urea nitrogens** \u2192 strongly **deactivated for protonation**.\n  - Only potentially basic site is **pyridine N** (pKa typically ~5\u20136; often mostly unprotonated at pH 7.4 but can be partially protonated depending on environment).",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:36:59.361223+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "790c4b27",
      "step_index": 3,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "**Structural alerts relevant to CYP2D6 inhibition**\n- Has **lipophilic aromatic rings** (fits one major feature).\n- **Lacks a classic protonatable tertiary aliphatic amine** (a common hallmark of strong CYP2D6 inhibitors like many antidepressants/antipsychotics).\n- Contains **multiple amide carbonyls** \u2192 increases polarity and reduces basicity (often reduces CYP2D6 binding/inhibition vs cationic amines).",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:36:59.361248+00:00"
    },
