    {
      "step_id": "dd045918",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "CYP2D6 inhibitors typically present:\n- A **positively charged/basic center** (often a tertiary amine) to engage the enzyme\u2019s acidic residue (commonly Asp301) via ionic interaction.\n- **Aromatic/lipophilic regions** to occupy hydrophobic pockets.\n- Often a **H-bond donor/acceptor pattern** near the basic center.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:36:59.361292+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "e387a58d",
      "step_index": 6,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "For this molecule:\n- **Basic center is weak/absent:**  \n  - The aliphatic nitrogens are tied up as **amide/urea** \u2192 essentially **non-basic** and **not cationic** at physiological pH.\n  - The **pyridine N** is only **moderately basic** and is not a \u201ccationic anchor\u201d comparable to a tertiary amine; even if partially protonated, its geometry/electronics differ from typical CYP2D6 inhibitor pharmacophores.\n- **Aromaticity is present:** phenyl + pyridine can support hydrophobic binding, but **without a strong cationic anchor**, binding affinity and inhibitory potency are usually lower.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:36:59.361313+00:00"
